    <stitle>DT 466 / DT 570 / HT 570 Service Manual - 2004 Emissions with EGR - Cylinder Head and Valve Train -
        Reconditioning - Resurfacing Valve Seats
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="S2650501.5" graphiccount="4">
        <title>Resurfacing Valve Seats</title>
        <figure id="f2650539" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figH08/H08027.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Installing valve guide pilot</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Lightly lubricate the correct size of grinding pilot. Install the pilot into the valve
                guide.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Choose the correct angle grinding stone and dress the stone. See "Specifications" for the
                correct valve seat angle.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install the grinding stone over the pilot.</para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f26505recon21" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figH08/H08028.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Grinding the valve seat</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Motor and drive</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Holder</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Grindstone</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Turn on the power and gently apply the weight of the grinding motor to the grindstone. Raise
                the grinding stone frequently to prevent overheating. Grind the valve seat to a smooth even finish,
                paying attention to achieving an acceptable uniform width .
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f2650540" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figH08/H08008.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Checking valve seat width</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a caliper to check the valve seat width. If the valve seat width exceeds specifications,
                the valve seat may be corrected by grinding with a 15 degree or smaller angle stone.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f2650541" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figH08/H08009.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Checking valve recession</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install valve in guide. Use a depth micrometer to check valve recession. If valve recession
                is excessive, install a new valve or replace valve seat as necessary. If the valve protrudes above the
                surface of the cylinder head, regrind the valve seat. After grinding the valve seat, check valve seat
                width again. Also
                <hotlnk document="eges2651_92.xml" xrefid="svcsubproc001" appearance="hottext">check the valve
                    face-to-valve seat contact</hotlnk>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use an appropriate dial indicator to check the valve seat runout. If runout exceeds
                specifications, replace valve seat.
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
